definition: "Trimethylamine N-oxide (TMAO) is a small molecule produced through a two-step metabolic pathway that links dietary intake to gut microbiome composition to cardiovascular risk. Step one: gut bacteria metabolize dietary choline, phosphatidylcholine (lecithin), and carnitine — found primarily in red meat, eggs, and fish — into trimethylamine (TMA). Step two: TMA is absorbed from the gut and oxidized in the liver by the enzyme flavin-containing monooxygenase 3 (FMO3) into TMAO. Circulating TMAO is then filtered by the kidneys and excreted in urine. The entire process is gut-microbiome-dependent: individuals whose gut bacteria lack the TMA-producing metabolic capacity produce negligible TMAO even when consuming large amounts of choline and carnitine."
why_it_matters: "TMAO is the first identified direct mechanistic link between the gut microbiome and atherosclerosis — a discovery that upended cardiovascular biology when it was first published in 2011. Elevated TMAO promotes atherosclerosis through multiple mechanisms: it impairs reverse cholesterol transport (reducing the ability of HDL to extract cholesterol from arterial plaques), promotes macrophage foam cell formation in arterial walls, activates platelet reactivity (increasing thrombotic risk), and drives endothelial dysfunction. Prospective clinical studies have found that TMAO levels in the upper quartile are associated with a 2.5–3× higher risk of major cardiovascular events over 3–7 year follow-up periods, independent of conventional risk factors including LDL, blood pressure, and diabetes status. TMAO also predicts mortality in heart failure, chronic kidney disease, and other conditions where gut dysbiosis is prevalent."

